02:41.529 --> 02:43.190
Robin Williger.

02:43.297 --> 02:46.892
He is a 15-year-old freshman
from Racine, Wisconsin.

02:47.001 --> 02:48.696
He enjoys studying history.

02:48.802 --> 02:50.429
He's on the debate team.

02:50.538 --> 02:53.803
Robin's future looked
very, very bright,

02:53.908 --> 02:55.739
but recently he was
diagnosed with cancer,

02:55.843 --> 02:57.401
a very tough kind of cancer.

02:57.511 --> 03:01.072
<i>Robin tells me he has</i>
<i>quit smoking, though,</i>

03:01.182 --> 03:04.413
and he no longer thinks
that cigarettes are cool.

03:08.556 --> 03:10.854
Whoo!

03:10.958 --> 03:14.223
And our final guest today
is Nick Naylor.

03:14.328 --> 03:18.890
Mr. Naylor is the vice president
of the Academy of Tobacco Studies.

03:18.999 --> 03:22.025
Now, they are the tobacco
industry's main lobby

03:22.136 --> 03:23.433
in Washington, D.C.

03:23.537 --> 03:26.597
And Mr. Naylor is
their chief spokesman.

03:44.592 --> 03:46.389
<i>Few people on this planet know</i>

03:46.493 --> 03:48.620
<i>what it is to be truly despised.</i>

03:48.729 --> 03:50.959
<i>Can you blame them?</i>

03:51.065 --> 03:53.431
<i>I earn a living</i>
<i>fronting an organization</i>

03:53.534 --> 03:56.799
<i>that kills 1,200 human beings a day.</i>

03:56.904 --> 03:58.098
<i>1,200 people.</i>

03:58.205 --> 04:00.696
<i>We're talking</i>
<i>two jumbojet plane loads</i>

04:00.808 --> 04:03.504
<i>of men, women and children.</i>

04:03.611 --> 04:04.635
<i>I mean, there's Attila,</i>

04:04.745 --> 04:06.269
<i>Genghis,</i>

04:06.380 --> 04:07.330
<i>and me,</i>

04:07.430 --> 04:08.643
<i>Nick Naylor,</i>

04:08.749 --> 04:09.773
<i>the face of cigarettes...</i>

04:09.883 --> 04:12.647
<i>the Colonel Sanders of nicotine.</i>

04:12.753 --> 04:14.220
<i>This is where I work,</i>

04:14.321 --> 04:16.846
<i>the Academy of Tobacco Studies.</i>

04:16.957 --> 04:19.118
<i>It was established</i>
<i>by seven gentlemen</i>

04:19.226 --> 04:20.817
<i>you may recognize from C-SPAN.</i>

04:20.928 --> 04:23.556
<i>These guys realized quick</i>
<i>if they were going to claim</i>

04:23.664 --> 04:24.756
<i>that cigarettes were not addictive,</i>

04:24.865 --> 04:27.026
<i>they better have proof.</i>

04:27.134 --> 04:28.965
<i>This is the man they rely on,</i>

04:29.069 --> 04:31.196
<i>Erhardt Von Grupten Mundt.</i>

04:31.305 --> 04:33.569
<i>They found him in Germany.</i>

04:33.674 --> 04:35.198
<i>I won't go into the details.</i>

04:35.309 --> 04:36.469
<i>He's been testing the link</i>

04:36.577 --> 04:37.805
<i>between nicotine</i>
<i>and lung cancer</i>

04:37.911 --> 04:41.176
<i>for 30 years and hasn't found</i>
<i>any conclusive results.</i>

04:41.282 --> 04:42.232
<i>The man's a genius.</i>

04:42.332 --> 04:43.944
<i>He could disprove gravity.</i>

04:44.051 --> 04:45.712
<i>Then we've got our sharks.</i>

04:45.819 --> 04:47.582
<i>We draft them out</i>
<i>of Ivy League law schools</i>

04:47.688 --> 04:49.986
<i>and give them time-shares</i>
<i>and sports cars.</i>

04:50.090 --> 04:51.648
<i>It's just like</i>
<i>a John Grisham novel-</i>

04:51.759 --> 04:54.319
<i>you know, without all the espionage.</i>

04:54.428 --> 04:57.659
<i>Most importantly,</i>
<i>we've got spin control.</i>

04:57.765 --> 04:59.596
<i>That's where I come in.</i>

04:59.700 --> 05:01.065
<i>I get paid to talk.</i>

05:01.168 --> 05:02.726
<i>I don't have an MD or law degree.</i>

05:05.172 --> 05:08.335
<i>I have a bachelor's in</i>
<i>kicking ass and taking names.</i>

05:08.442 --> 05:10.876
<i>You know that guy</i>
<i>who can pick up any girl?</i>

05:10.978 --> 05:12.036
<i>I'm him</i>

05:12.146 --> 05:13.238
<i>on crack.</i>

05:16.550 --> 05:18.541
This is obviously a heated issue

05:18.652 --> 05:21.348
and we do have a lot
that we want to cover today.

05:22.289 --> 05:23.551
Nick, do you have a question?

05:23.657 --> 05:24.749
Joan,

05:24.858 --> 05:28.658
how on earth would
Big Tobacco profit

05:28.762 --> 05:31.196
off of the loss of this young man?

05:31.298 --> 05:33.493
Now, I hate to think
in such callous terms,

05:33.600 --> 05:36.694
but, if anything,
we'd be losing a customer.

05:36.804 --> 05:39.898
It's not only our hope,
it's in our best interest

05:40.007 --> 05:42.237
to keep Robin alive and smoking.

05:42.343 --> 05:44.004
- That's ludicrous.
- Let me tell you something,

05:44.111 --> 05:45.942
Joan, and please,
let me share something

05:46.046 --> 05:49.675
with the fine, concerned
people in the audience today.

05:49.783 --> 05:53.344
The Ron Goodes of this world...

05:53.454 --> 05:56.014
want the Robin Willigers to die.

05:56.123 --> 05:57.215
- What?
- You know why?

05:57.324 --> 05:58.916
So that their budgets will go up.

05:59.026 --> 06:01.893
This is nothing less than
trafficking in human misery,

06:01.995 --> 06:03.758
and you, sir, ought
to be ashamed of yourself.

06:03.864 --> 06:05.354
I ought to be ashamed of myself?

06:05.466 --> 06:08.594
As a matter of fact,
we're about to launch...

06:08.702 --> 06:11.694
a $50 million campaign

06:11.805 --> 06:15.969
aimed at persuading kids
not to smoke.

06:16.076 --> 06:18.237
Because I think
that we can all agree

06:18.345 --> 06:20.472
that there is nothing
more important

06:20.581 --> 06:21.912
than America's children.

06:22.015 --> 06:23.380
All right, now,
that's something that

06:23.484 --> 06:25.247
we're going to want
to know more about.

06:25.352 --> 06:26.512
But I have to take a short break.

06:26.620 --> 06:28.713
Hang on, a lot more coming.

06:31.692 --> 06:34.627
$50 million?! Are you
out of your fucking mind?!

06:34.728 --> 06:35.678
<i>Everyone has a boss.</i>

06:35.778 --> 06:36.679
<i>BR just happens</i>

06:36.779 --> 06:38.254
<i>to be mine.</i>

06:38.365 --> 06:40.230
<i>He came from the vending</i>
<i>machine world.</i>

06:40.334 --> 06:41.995
<i>This made him tough.</i>

06:43.370 --> 06:46.567
<i>The name BR came</i>
<i>from his tour in Vietnam.</i>

06:46.673 --> 06:49.767
<i>The people who know</i>
<i>its meaning are all dead.</i>

06:49.877 --> 06:51.310
The deal was five million!

06:51.412 --> 06:54.176
$5 million will get you
a couple of subway posters.

06:54.281 --> 06:55.248
It's not going to impress anyone.

06:55.348 --> 06:56.475
That's the idea, Nick.

06:56.583 --> 06:57.550
You'll be thanking me soon.

06:57.650 --> 06:58.778
This'll probably get you great press.

06:58.886 --> 07:01.252
I gotta call the captain
and see if this is gonna fly.

07:01.355 --> 07:03.448
Get your ass back to D.C.

07:17.271 --> 07:19.239
Thank you so much for coming.

07:21.074 --> 07:22.024
Mr. Naylor?

07:22.124 --> 07:23.075
It's your turn.

07:23.177 --> 07:25.509
Ah.

07:25.612 --> 07:27.671
Joey is such a bright young man.

07:27.781 --> 07:28.765
We all look forward

07:28.865 --> 07:30.612
to his coming out
of his shell a little.

07:30.717 --> 07:31.945
He's a bit shy.

07:32.052 --> 07:33.849
Yeah, he gets that from his mother.

07:42.996 --> 07:45.760
Hey, Joey.

07:45.866 --> 07:48.232
Please don't ruin my childhood.

07:48.335 --> 07:50.394
Come on, Joey. Trust me.

07:58.312 --> 08:01.372
How many of you want to be
lawyers when you grow up?

08:01.482 --> 08:02.482
Right.

08:02.583 --> 08:04.073
How about...

08:04.184 --> 08:05.913
movie stars?

08:07.354 --> 08:08.480
How about lobbyists?

08:08.589 --> 08:09.556
What's that?

08:09.656 --> 08:11.557
It's kind of like being a movie star.

08:11.658 --> 08:13.421
It's what I do.
I talk for a living.

08:13.527 --> 08:14.687
What do you talk about?

08:14.795 --> 08:16.854
I speak on behalf of cigarettes.

08:16.964 --> 08:18.192
My mom used to smoke.

08:18.298 --> 08:20.926
She says that cigarettes kill.

08:21.034 --> 08:23.434
Really? Now, is your mommy a doctor?

08:23.537 --> 08:24.487
No.

08:24.587 --> 08:26.267
A scientific researcher of some kind?

08:26.373 --> 08:27.601
No.

08:27.708 --> 08:28.675
Well, she doesn't exactly sound

08:28.775 --> 08:30.141
like a credible expert,
now, does she?

08:31.678 --> 08:32.628
Don't feel bad.

08:32.727 --> 08:34.578
It's okay to listen to your mom.

08:34.681 --> 08:37.047
I mean, it's good to listen
to your parents... Joey.

08:37.150 --> 08:39.448
All I'm suggesting

08:39.553 --> 08:41.953
is that there will always
be people trying to tell you

08:42.054 --> 08:44.216
what to do and what to think.

08:44.324 --> 08:45.689
There probably already are
people doing that.

08:45.792 --> 08:46.742
Am I right?

08:46.842 --> 08:47.760
Yes.

08:47.860 --> 08:49.591
I'm here to say

08:49.696 --> 08:53.132
that when someone tries to act
like some sort of an expert,

08:53.233 --> 08:56.725
you can respond, "Who says?"

08:56.837 --> 08:58.532
<i>So, cigarettes are good for you?</i>

08:58.639 --> 09:00.539
- No!
- No, that's not...

09:00.641 --> 09:01.801
That's not what I'm getting at.

09:01.909 --> 09:04.241
My point is that you have
to think for yourself.

09:04.344 --> 09:06.073
You have to challenge authority.

09:06.179 --> 09:08.443
If your parents told you
that chocolate was dangerous,

09:08.549 --> 09:10.073
would you just take their word for it?

09:10.183 --> 09:11.275
No.

09:11.385 --> 09:12.385
Exactly.

09:12.486 --> 09:14.317
So perhaps instead of acting
like sheep

09:14.421 --> 09:15.405
when it comes to cigarettes,

09:15.505 --> 09:16.922
you should find out for yourself.

09:17.024 --> 09:18.150
Okay, then.

09:18.258 --> 09:20.624
Thank you, Mr. Naylor,
for joining us.

09:30.103 --> 09:32.663
<i>Every week we meet here at Bert's.</i>

09:32.773 --> 09:34.764
<i>Together, we represent</i>
<i>the chief spokespeople</i>

09:34.875 --> 09:37.844
<i>for the tobacco, alcohol and</i>
<i>firearms industries.</i>

09:37.945 --> 09:39.071
<i>We call ourselves the MOD Squad.</i>

09:39.179 --> 09:40.129
All right.

09:40.229 --> 09:42.842
<i>M-O-D, Merchants of Death.</i>

09:42.950 --> 09:44.110
So, my day's ruined.

09:44.217 --> 09:45.167
Why?

09:45.267 --> 09:46.446
<i>Dateline's doing a segment</i>

09:46.553 --> 09:48.145
on fatal alcohol syndrome.
Thank you.

09:48.255 --> 09:50.189
<i>Polly works</i>
<i>for the Moderation Council.</i>

09:50.290 --> 09:52.588
<i>A casual drinker</i>
<i>by the age of 14,</i>

09:52.693 --> 09:53.955
<i>Polly quickly developed</i>

09:54.061 --> 09:57.462
<i>a tolerance usually reserved</i>
<i>for Irish dockworkers.</i>

09:57.564 --> 09:59.395
<i>In our world, she's the woman</i>

09:59.499 --> 10:01.660
<i>that got the pope</i>
<i>to endorse red wine.</i>

10:04.638 --> 10:05.605
We're gonna get creamed.

10:05.705 --> 10:06.934
Any ideas?

10:07.040 --> 10:08.337
I don't know.

10:08.442 --> 10:10.774
Deformed kids are tough.

10:10.877 --> 10:13.141
I'm lucky my product only makes
them bald before it kills them.

10:13.246 --> 10:15.146
You could hug the kids.

10:15.248 --> 10:17.216
They're not going
to let me hug the kids.

10:17.317 --> 10:18.875
Who's doing the segment,
Donaldson or Sawyer?

10:18.986 --> 10:19.936
Sawyer, probably.

10:20.036 --> 10:20.937
You're fucked.

10:21.037 --> 10:21.938
Why?

10:22.038 --> 10:23.115
Cause she's gonna hug them.

10:23.223 --> 10:25.418
Look, if you see her going in
for a hug,

10:25.525 --> 10:28.358
maybe just box her out,
get in there before she does.

10:28.462 --> 10:30.054
<i>Bobby Jay works for SAFETY,</i>

10:30.163 --> 10:32.393
<i>the Society for the Advancement of Firearms</i>

10:32.499 --> 10:34.296
<i>and Effective Training for Youth.</i>

10:34.401 --> 10:36.699
You want me to smile?

10:38.472 --> 10:40.872
<i>After watching the footage</i>
<i>of the Kent State shootings,</i>

10:40.974 --> 10:43.807
<i>Bobby Jay, then 17, signed up</i>
<i>for the National Guard</i>

10:43.910 --> 10:46.003
<i>so he, too, could shoot</i>
<i>college students.</i>

10:46.113 --> 10:48.581
<i>But the National Guard</i>
<i>recruiter was out to lunch,</i>

10:48.682 --> 10:51.845
<i>so Bobby Jay ended up</i>
<i>shooting Panamanians instead,</i>

10:51.952 --> 10:53.613
<i>which was almost as good</i>
<i>as college students.</i>

10:54.855 --> 10:56.652
<i>Only they shoot back.</i>

10:56.757 --> 10:58.418
You know, you can beat
a Breathalyzer

10:58.525 --> 11:01.517
- by sucking on activated charcoal tablets?
- Really?

11:01.628 --> 11:03.186
Maybe we should change
our campaign to

11:03.296 --> 11:05.264
"If You Must Drink and Drive,
Suck Charcoal."

11:05.365 --> 11:06.423
Yeah, but don't the police wonder

11:06.533 --> 11:07.483
why you're sucking on charcoal?

11:07.583 --> 11:09.331
There's no law against charcoal.

11:09.436 --> 11:10.926
- Yet.
- Yet.

11:15.809 --> 11:18.801
Dad, why is the American
government the best government?

11:18.912 --> 11:20.436
Because of our
endless appeals system.

11:23.550 --> 11:26.075
Joe, you're not writing down
what I just said are you?

11:26.186 --> 11:27.346
Mm-hmm.

11:27.454 --> 11:29.445
Joey, stop for a second.

11:29.556 --> 11:31.046
What is the subject of your essay?

11:31.158 --> 11:33.956
Why is American government
the best government in the world.

11:34.061 --> 11:35.688
Your teacher crafted that question?

11:35.796 --> 11:37.559
Yeah. Why?

11:37.664 --> 11:40.462
Well... I'll look past
the obvious problems

11:40.567 --> 11:41.864
in syntax for a moment,

11:41.968 --> 11:44.061
and I'll focus more on the core
of the question.

11:44.171 --> 11:45.365
I mean, "A,"

11:45.472 --> 11:48.100
does America have
the best government in the world?

11:48.208 --> 11:49.869
And "B," what constitutes
a "best government"?

11:49.976 --> 11:52.410
Is it crime, is it poverty, literacy?

11:52.512 --> 11:53.945
Hmm?

11:54.047 --> 11:55.014
And America- definitely not best.

11:55.114 --> 11:56.276
Perhaps not even better than most.

11:56.383 --> 11:57.748
We do have a very
entertaining government...

11:57.851 --> 11:59.148
Dad.

11:59.252 --> 12:01.083
I'm sorry.

12:02.389 --> 12:04.823
Are you familiar with the term "B.S."?

12:04.925 --> 12:06.483
Bullshit.

12:06.593 --> 12:07.855
Yes, exactly.

12:07.961 --> 12:10.862
B.S., if I may, is what
questions like the one

12:10.964 --> 12:12.864
your teacher posed are made for.

12:12.966 --> 12:14.900
Because even if America
had the best government,

12:15.001 --> 12:16.525
there'd be no way to prove it.

12:16.636 --> 12:17.967
And how many pages are you writing?

12:18.071 --> 12:19.021
Two pages.

12:19.121 --> 12:20.664
Two pages...

12:20.774 --> 12:22.332
Definitely not in two pages.

12:22.442 --> 12:24.603
So what am I supposed to write?

12:24.711 --> 12:26.406
You can write whatever you want.

12:26.513 --> 12:27.912
Okay.

12:28.014 --> 12:29.014
Write about...

12:29.116 --> 12:31.516
write about America's
amazing ability

12:31.618 --> 12:34.610
to make profit by breaking down
trading tariffs

12:34.721 --> 12:37.087
and bringing American jobs
to Third World countries.

12:37.190 --> 12:39.124
Or how good we are
at executing felons.

12:39.226 --> 12:40.853
They're all correct answers.

12:40.961 --> 12:42.929
I can do that?

12:43.029 --> 12:44.553
See, Joey, that's the beauty
of argument.

12:44.664 --> 12:47.064
'Cause if you argue correctly,
you're never wrong.

12:54.775 --> 12:57.676
Dad, if I finish
this essay within an hour,

12:57.778 --> 12:59.541
can we stay up all night?

12:59.646 --> 13:04.310
That's a negotiation,
not an argument.

13:04.417 --> 13:07.147
Well, Conway, see you made it.

13:07.254 --> 13:09.279
Yeah, I guess that little
voice was wrong.

13:09.389 --> 13:10.481
I feel better.

13:10.590 --> 13:11.750
I feel a lot better, too.

13:11.858 --> 13:14.418
As a matter of fact, I never
felt so good in my life.

13:14.528 --> 13:16.120
How about a cigarette?

13:32.979 --> 13:34.071
Is he?

13:34.181 --> 13:35.273
Yeah.

13:37.384 --> 13:40.820
Hey.

13:40.921 --> 13:44.357
Nick, you still own a watch, don't you?

13:44.457 --> 13:45.651
Jill, I can't help feeling

13:45.759 --> 13:47.283
Joey's getting the wrong idea
about his dad.

13:47.394 --> 13:48.918
It would be great if I could spend

13:49.029 --> 13:50.553
a little more time with him,
you know?

13:50.664 --> 13:54.156
To give him a fair
and balanced perspective.

13:54.267 --> 13:56.132
Nick, you had plenty
of time for that.

13:56.236 --> 13:57.703
Now you're his weekend guardian.

13:57.804 --> 13:59.829
Besides, he has Brad.

13:59.940 --> 14:01.032
He still needs his father.

14:01.141 --> 14:03.336
Nick.

14:03.443 --> 14:04.535
You have a second?

14:06.246 --> 14:07.577
Sure, Brad.

14:07.681 --> 14:11.447
Nick, your job
and everything aside,

14:11.551 --> 14:13.485
I hope you understand
that secondhand smoke's

14:13.587 --> 14:15.282
a real killer.

14:15.388 --> 14:17.253
What are you talking about?

14:17.357 --> 14:18.984
I just hope you're providing

14:19.092 --> 14:21.652
a smoke-free environment
for Joey, that's all I'm saying.

14:21.761 --> 14:23.956
Brad, I'm his father.

14:24.064 --> 14:26.396
You're the guy fucking his mom.

14:28.802 --> 14:31.100
That was unnecessary.

14:31.271 --> 14:34.707
Thank you all.
Thank you all for coming.

14:34.808 --> 14:37.276
Tobacco is winning the war.

14:37.377 --> 14:40.574
The war against our children.

14:40.680 --> 14:43.979
They like to use cartoons
and symbols to hook our kids.

14:44.084 --> 14:46.951
Well, now we have
a symbol of our own.

14:47.053 --> 14:49.248
Doctor.

14:49.356 --> 14:52.120
It is my hope that
within the year

14:52.225 --> 14:53.920
every cigarette package

14:54.027 --> 14:57.053
sold in America
will carry this symbol.

14:57.163 --> 14:59.393
Perhaps then, cigarettes
will finally be labeled

14:59.499 --> 15:02.593
appropriately as poison.

15:02.702 --> 15:04.567
I will be holding
a congressional hearing

15:04.671 --> 15:07.401
to discuss the inclusion
of the skull and crossbones

15:07.507 --> 15:08.974
in the next two weeks.

15:09.075 --> 15:10.474
As usual, I extend
an open invitation

15:10.577 --> 15:13.068
to big tobacco.

15:13.179 --> 15:17.172
Perhaps this time they will
grace us with their presence.

15:17.284 --> 15:18.581
And their answers.

15:18.685 --> 15:20.084
Thank you very much.

15:24.791 --> 15:28.227
People, what is going on out there?

15:28.328 --> 15:31.957
I look down this table,
all I see are white flags.

15:32.065 --> 15:34.693
Our numbers are down
all across the board.

15:34.801 --> 15:36.666
Teen smoking-
our bread and butter,

15:36.770 --> 15:38.499
is falling like a shit from heaven.

15:40.640 --> 15:42.301
We don't sell Tic Tacs,
for Christ's sake.

15:42.409 --> 15:44.070
We sell cigarettes.

15:44.177 --> 15:48.113
And they're cool and available
and addictive.

15:48.214 --> 15:49.841
The job is almost done for us.

15:51.618 --> 15:56.521
This environmentalist
is challenging us.

15:56.623 --> 15:59.183
We have to have an answer.

